&lt;p>&#xD;
    For details on the requirements for safety analysis (as the form of the analysis is very dependent upon the ASIL level&#xD;
    being analyzed) it is recommended that the user refer to ISO 26262, volume 5, clause 7.4.3. This covers information&#xD;
    regarding single, double, and multi point failures.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For details of analysis regarding dependent failures, which is the basis for compliance of HW design to independent&#xD;
    failures, the user should refer to ISO 26262, volume 9, clause 7.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In the case of of hazards introduced by the intended design,&amp;nbsp; the change management strategy outlined in ISO&#xD;
    26262, volume 8, clause 8 should be applied.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    It is recommended that users refer to ISO 26262, volume 5 annex B for information regarding failure mode classification of&#xD;
    an element.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    FMEA and FTA can be used as a means to aid the HW safety analysis, this can be carried out using model based approaches&#xD;
    detailed in &lt;a class=&quot;elementLink&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../practice.tech.real_time.safe_rel_analysis.base-ibm/guidances/practices/safe_rel_an_966E315A.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_2BtTQLePEd-05egMquN4Dg&quot;>Safety and Reliability Analysis&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
